"""
MKT Context Commentary — Proverbs chapters 10–12
Run: python3 scripts/zc-context-proverbs-10-12.py

Source data used:
- data/interlinear/proverbs.json
- data/translation/glossary-hebrew.json
- data/translation/draft/mediating/proverbs.json

Key decisions in this range:
- Chs 10–12 are the opening of the Solomonic sentence collection (10:1–22:16), where
  the extended father-to-son discourses of chs 1–9 give way to two-line antithetic
  mashal couplets. Context commentary for these chapters focuses on the social world
  behind the couplets: commerce ethics, honor-shame dynamics, the agrarian economy,
  and the gate-court legal context.
- The dominant contrastive structure (righteous vs. wicked) reflects the bi-polar
  moral world of Israelite wisdom, not a naïve prosperity gospel. The contrast is the
  pedagogical form; real-life complexity is handled by other proverbs elsewhere in the
  collection.
- 11:30 "tree of life" is an Eden allusion (Gen 2–3), not cosmology.
- 12:4 "eshet hayil" (excellent/capable wife) is the same phrase as Prov 31:10 — a
  term of military strength applied to domestic virtue.
"""

import json, pathlib

ROOT = pathlib.Path(__file__).parent.parent

def load_comm(source, book):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    if p.exists():
        return json.loads(p.read_text())
    return {}

def save_comm(source, book, data):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    p.parent.mkdir(parents=True, exist_ok=True)
    p.write_text(json.dumps(data, ensure_ascii=False, indent=None))
    print(f'  wrote {p.relative_to(ROOT)}')

def merge_comm(existing, new_data):
    """Merge new_data into existing without overwriting present entries."""
    for ch, verses in new_data.items():
        if ch not in existing:
            existing[ch] = {}
        for v, html in verses.items():
            if v not in existing[ch]:
                existing[ch][v] = html

PROVERBS = {
  "10": {
    "1": "<p>The superscription <em>mishle shelomoh</em> (proverbs of Solomon) marks a decisive structural break from chs 1–9. The extended discourses, direct addresses, and personified Wisdom of the prologue give way to two-line sentence proverbs — the <em>mashal</em> in its classic antithetic form. Chs 10–22:16 constitute the oldest identifiable Solomonic layer of the book. The content of v1 — son/father and son/mother grief — places the collection immediately within the household as the primary unit of moral formation in ancient Israel; the intergenerational relationship between parent and child was both the site of wisdom transmission and the first locus of the honor-shame dynamic.</p>",
    "2": "<p>Ill-gotten wealth (<em>otzarot resha'</em> — treasuries/stores of wickedness) was a recognized category of commercial misconduct in the ANE. Overcharging, false weights, lending at interest (prohibited within Israel, Exod 22:25), and seizure of pledges were the common mechanisms. The pairing with <em>tzedaqah</em> (righteousness/right-dealing) as the deliverer from death (<em>mavet</em>) reflects the covenantal claim that commercial ethics is a life-or-death matter — not metaphorically but because the social order sustained by honest commerce was the order in which life could be lived. The lex talionis of commercial justice: extraction from others extracts one&rsquo;s own life.</p>",
    "3": "<p>The hunger-of-the-righteous / craving-of-the-wicked contrast reflects the subsistence reality of ancient Israelite economy. Most households operated near the margin; starvation was a genuine risk in drought years. The theological claim is not that the righteous are always prosperous but that YHWH&rsquo;s provision is tied to right-ordering — a claim set within the covenantal framework where faithfulness to the covenant community&rsquo;s ethical norms was the condition of land-blessing (Deut 28). The contrast of <em>nefesh</em> (the whole person&rsquo;s appetite/soul) with the <em>haved</em> (craving/desire) of the wicked: the wicked desire more than their share; the righteous receive what suffices.</p>",
    "4": "<p>The agricultural economy of ancient Israel was labor-intensive and seasonal. The contrast of the <em>kaf remiyyah</em> (slack hand, the hand of deceit/negligence) with the <em>yad charuzim</em> (hand of the diligent/industrious) reflects the direct connection between labor application and harvest yield in a pre-mechanized farming context. Poverty (<em>rosh</em>) as the result of laziness was not a moral abstraction but a readily observable agricultural fact: planting, weeding, and harvest timing were critical, and those who missed them faced food insecurity. The proverb is observational wisdom, not a denial that structural poverty exists.</p>",
    "5": "<p>The agricultural calendar was the organizing structure of ancient Israelite life. The summer harvest (primarily grain) was a concentrated, time-sensitive operation requiring all available household labor. A son who slept through the harvest was not merely lazy in a personal sense but was failing his family&rsquo;s social obligation: harvest was communal, neighbors relied on neighbors, and the shame of the sleeping son reflected on the household. The term <em>mevishs</em> (brings shame, causes shame) is the honor-shame vocabulary applied to the agricultural context: social standing tracked with visible diligence.</p>",
    "6": "<p>The idiom &ldquo;the mouth of the wicked conceals violence&rdquo; (<em>uchfi resha'im yechassé chamas</em>) — repeated in v11 — is a paradoxical formulation: the mouth that should produce speech instead conceals violence. In the honor-shame world, a person&rsquo;s speech was their primary social instrument; the mouth that could not speak honest words was a mouth that had been corrupted from its purpose. <em>Chamas</em> (violence, H2555) carries the connotation of social disruption and injustice — the violence done to the social fabric — rather than only physical violence. The blessing crown on the righteous head is the public honor visible in the community.</p>",
    "7": "<p>In ancient Israelite culture, the <em>shem</em> (name) was the vehicle of social immortality. One did not live beyond death in a robust personal sense (Sheol was a shadowy non-existence), but one&rsquo;s <em>shem</em> persisted in the community&rsquo;s memory. To have one&rsquo;s name &ldquo;rot&rdquo; (<em>yirqav</em>) was the worst possible social outcome — worse than death, because it meant the annihilation of the only form of continuity available. This is why acts of loyalty and righteousness were so central: they built the <em>shem</em> that would outlast the person. The contrast of blessing-memory with rotting-name is a contrast between two kinds of social afterlife.</p>",
    "8": "<p>The <em>chakham lev</em> (wise in heart) who accepts instruction (<em>yiqbach mitzvot</em>) is the person whose formation has created receptivity to guidance — the quality that Proverbs consistently identifies as the foundation of all further wisdom. <em>Yiqbach</em> (to take, to receive, H6901) used here is the idiom for receiving instruction as a physical taking of a gift. The babbling fool (<em>'evil sefatayim</em>, the fool of lips) who comes to ruin is the one whose speech is unrestrained by formation — the socially dangerous person who says what he thinks without the filter of wisdom. In the gate-court context where much of Israelite life was conducted, the undisciplined talker was a liability.</p>",
    "9": "<p>The man who walks in <em>tom</em> (integrity/completeness — the same root as the Urim/Thummim, the oracle stones of the priestly breastplate) walks in <em>betach</em> (security, confidence). The <em>tom</em>-walker is the person whose inner and outer life are integrated — what they present to the community is what they actually are. The contrast: the one who twists his ways (<em>meaqqesh derakav</em>) will be exposed (<em>yivvadea'</em>, to be known/revealed). Public exposure was the mechanism of social accountability in the gatecourt community where everyone&rsquo;s affairs were eventually known. Integrity did not prevent scrutiny; it survived it.</p>",
    "10": "<p>The winking eye (<em>qoretze 'ayin</em>) is a physical gesture of conspiratorial communication — the covert signal between accomplices. The ANE evidence for eye-signaling as a gesture of malice and conspiracy is well-attested: it appears in Egyptian wisdom texts and in Psalms 35:19 as the gesture of the enemy who rejoices over the sufferer. In the honor-shame context, the overt mock and the covert wink represent two modes of social harm: the babbling fool is openly foolish, but the winker is actively malicious in a concealed way, making the wink the more dangerous form.</p>",
    "11": "<p>The fountain of life (<em>meqor chayyim</em>) as a metaphor for the mouth of the righteous uses the water-source imagery central to the Palestinian physical geography — springs were scarce and precious. A fountain provides not merely temporary refreshment but a continuous source: the righteous person&rsquo;s speech is generative, creating the conditions for social life to flourish around it. The inversion of this metaphor in the second half — the mouth of the wicked conceals violence — presents the corrupted water source (cf. the springs-and-wells imagery of the OT as a whole where water corruption is a sign of covenant violation).</p>",
    "12": "<p><em>Sinah</em> (hatred, H8135) as the stirrer of conflict and <em>ahavah</em> (love/loyalty, H160) as the cover of offenses reflects the honor-shame dynamic of communal life: hatred publicizes offenses (shaming them before the community), while <em>hesed</em>-style loyalty covers them (prevents public exposure). The &ldquo;covering&rdquo; (<em>yekasseh</em>) is not dishonest concealment but the active choice not to weaponize another&rsquo;s failure — the social practice of generosity toward the reputation of those in one&rsquo;s community. 1 Peter 4:8 quotes this verse directly in the context of the church community.</p>",
    "13": "<p>The rod on the back of the senseless (<em>chaser lev</em>, the one who lacks heart/judgment) is the instrument of communal correction for the person whose formation has failed. In the Israelite legal-social context, the rod (<em>shevet</em>) was both the shepherd&rsquo;s staff and the instrument of corporal correction authorized by the community (cf. Deut 25:2-3 where public beating was a regulated form of judicial punishment). The contrast with wisdom found on the lips of the discerning places the two instruments — wisdom-speech and the corrective rod — as alternatives: the teachable person receives wisdom through speech; the unteachable requires the rod.</p>",
    "14": "<p>The wise &ldquo;store up&rdquo; (<em>yitzpenu</em>) knowledge — the same root used for treasuries and hidden stores. Knowledge in the wisdom tradition is not merely the possession of information but the habit of accumulating observation and interpretation over time: the life-long formation of the wise person produces a stored resource. The fool&rsquo;s mouth brings destruction near (<em>mecharevet qerovah</em>, a destruction that is close) because untimely, uninformed speech in the gate-court context could provoke legal action, family conflict, or community censure. The nearness of the destruction is the wisdom observation: foolish speech produces consequences quickly.</p>",
    "15": "<p>The simile of the wealthy person&rsquo;s city (<em>qiryat uzzo</em>, his city of strength) reflects the physical reality of ancient Palestine: the walled city was the only security against attack, and wealth provided access to urban security. Peasants outside the walls were vulnerable to raiding; the wealthy could afford to live within the protection of walls. Poverty (<em>rosh</em>) as the &ldquo;ruin of the poor&rdquo; (<em>mechittat dallim</em>) is not moralizing but social observation: poverty in the ancient world meant exposure to all forms of vulnerability — famine, violence, legal disadvantage. The proverb does not endorse this state of affairs but describes its reality.</p>",
    "16": "<p>The contrasting destinations of earnings — life for the righteous, sin/transgression for the wicked — uses the economic vocabulary (<em>pe'ulat tzaddiq</em>, earnings/wages/work of the righteous) applied to moral outcomes. In the honor-shame economy, the direction of one&rsquo;s resources was not merely a financial but a social and theological matter: resources directed toward the community (generosity, hospitality, care for the poor) produced the social capital that Proverbs calls &ldquo;life.&rdquo; Resources directed toward self-aggrandizement at others&rsquo; expense produced the social liability that Proverbs calls &ldquo;sin.&rdquo;</p>",
    "17": "<p>The path of life (<em>orach chayyim</em>) as the metaphor for the instruction-keeping life reflects the way-imagery central to biblical anthropology — life as a journey with two roads rather than a static state. The one who keeps instruction (<em>shomer musar</em>) stays on the path; the one who abandons correction goes astray (<em>mat'eh</em>, causes to wander). The abandonment of correction in an oral-transmission culture meant cutting oneself off from the accumulated wisdom of the community that was transmitted through the formal instruction of family, village elders, and later scribal schools. To abandon <em>musar</em> was to choose isolation from the community&rsquo;s formative resources.</p>",
    "18": "<p>The pairing of lying lips with the concealment of hatred captures a specific social pathology: the person who presents a smooth exterior while harboring deep antagonism. In the honor-shame context, the concealment was not merely personal hypocrisy but a social strategy — the person who hides hatred through pleasant speech is gathering intelligence and waiting for the moment to strike. The term <em>dibbah</em> (slander, H1681, the spreading of evil report) is the weapon that emerges from the hidden hatred: slander weaponizes private knowledge of another&rsquo;s failings in the public forum.</p>",
    "19": "<p>The Israelite wisdom tradition consistently counseled restraint in speech — not silence, but calibrated quantity. The connection between speech volume and sin reflects the social reality of the gatecourt world: where everyone had opinions about everyone else&rsquo;s affairs, the person who spoke much inevitably said things that were untrue, that violated confidence, or that created enmity. The <em>mechashek sefatav</em> (holder-back of lips, the one who restrains his lips) reflects the disciplined formation that Proverbs commends — not the withdrawal from community but the habit of speaking with selection and purpose. Ecclesiastes 5:2 makes the same point from the cultic angle: many words in prayer is like a fool&rsquo;s sacrifice.</p>",
    "20": "<p>The silver-tongue metaphor for the righteous contrasts with the little-value heart of the wicked. Silver was the primary currency of ancient Israel (gold was rarer and used for prestige items); the tongue/silver comparison values the righteous person&rsquo;s speech as the most functional social currency. The contrast of tongue (external speech) with heart (<em>lev</em>, the inner life, the seat of intention and formation) in the second half is a structural reversal: the righteous person&rsquo;s exterior (speech) is valuable; the wicked person&rsquo;s interior (heart) is worthless. The outside of one is worth more than the inside of the other.</p>",
    "21": "<p>The &ldquo;feeding&rdquo; done by the righteous person&rsquo;s lips (<em>sefatei tzaddiq yir'u rabbim</em> — the lips of the righteous shepherd/nourish many) applies the pastoral vocabulary of tending a flock to the social function of wise speech. The wise speaker is a community resource — their words feed those around them. This is not hyperbole in the context of an oral culture where wisdom teaching, mediation of disputes, and instructional speech were the primary mechanisms by which the community maintained its social order. The comparison of fools dying for lack of <em>lev</em> (heart/judgment) closes the circle: the resource that the wise offer (nourishing speech) is precisely what the fool lacks.</p>",
    "22": "<p>The theology of YHWH&rsquo;s blessing as the true source of wealth operates within the framework of the deuteronomic covenant: blessing flows from covenant faithfulness, not merely from human effort. The additional clause — &ldquo;he adds no sorrow to it&rdquo; (<em>ve-lo' yosif 'etzev 'immah</em>) — distinguishes YHWH-blessed wealth from wealth obtained through anxiety, exploitation, or social cost. Ill-gotten gain comes with the &ldquo;sorrow&rdquo; of sustained fear, relational damage, and divine displeasure; the <em>birkat YHWH</em> (blessing of the LORD) is the wealth that arrives clean of such costs. This is the wisdom tradition&rsquo;s qualitative distinction about sources of wealth.</p>",
    "23": "<p>The &ldquo;game&rdquo; (<em>zimmah</em>, H2154, evil plan/lewdness — better rendered as &ldquo;wickedness is a game/sport&rdquo;) idiom for the fool who treats wrongdoing as play reflects the social perception of the fool as someone without the emotional seriousness that moral formation requires. In an honor-shame culture, the inability to experience shame at wrongdoing was a fundamental social defect — the conscience-shaped community expected its members to feel the weight of transgression. The fool&rsquo;s levity about sin is therefore a social danger, not merely a personal failing: it introduces the contagion of moral weightlessness into the community.</p>",
    "24": "<p>The motif of the wicked receiving what they fear, and the righteous receiving what they long for, is the wisdom tradition&rsquo;s articulation of moral coherence in creation: the universe is ordered such that what one produces morally tends to return to one. This is not karma in the impersonal sense but the covenantal claim that YHWH&rsquo;s management of creation is oriented toward justice. The <em>ta'avat tzaddiqim</em> (longing/desire of the righteous) receiving fulfillment echoes the Psalter&rsquo;s theology of the righteous who wait on YHWH: the desire is for the restoration of right order, and YHWH is its guarantor.</p>",
    "25": "<p>The storm image (<em>ke'avar sufah</em>, when the whirlwind passes) for the sudden end of the wicked reflects the Palestinian experience of the <em>sufah</em> — the violent desert storm that appears without warning and passes through, leaving devastation. The wicked have no more permanent rootedness than the debris that the storm sweeps away. By contrast, the righteous stand on an <em>yesod 'olam</em> (everlasting foundation) — the word <em>yesod</em> (foundation, H3247) used for the deep foundations of a building, the kind of construction that survives storms. The image of the enduring foundation for the righteous anticipates the NT parable of the two builders (Matt 7:24-27).</p>",
    "26": "<p>The sour vinegar (<em>chometz</em>) to the teeth and smoke to the eyes are precise physical descriptions of physiological irritants: the acid sting of vinegar on sensitive teeth and the watering, forced-closure response to smoke. These are analogies for the lazy employee (<em>'atzel</em>, the sluggard, the classic wisdom failure-character) in relation to the one who sends him (<em>lesholeachav</em>, his senders/employers). The physical sensation is involuntary, immediate, and irritating; so is the sluggard&rsquo;s effect on those who depend on him. The observation is about the social cost of undependability in an economy where labor was critical and human reliability was the primary infrastructure.</p>",
    "27": "<p>The theology of the fear of the LORD (<em>yir'at YHWH</em>) as the lengthener of life (<em>tosif yamim</em> — adds days) is the wisdom tradition&rsquo;s positive formulation of covenantal blessing. Long life (<em>yamim</em>) was one of the core covenant blessings in Deuteronomy (4:40; 5:33; 6:2) — not life without end, but the full span of productive years in the community. The corresponding shortening (<em>vitiqtzrenu</em> — it cuts short) of the wicked&rsquo;s years reflects the observed correlation between social destructiveness and early death: violence, theft, and the social conflicts they generate statistically shortened the lives of those who engaged in them in the ancient world&rsquo;s pre-judicial context.</p>",
    "28": "<p><em>Tochelet tzaddiqim</em> (the hope/expectation of the righteous) producing joy and the <em>tiqvat resha'im</em> (hope of the wicked) coming to nothing uses the vocabulary of anticipation and outcome. In the ancient economy, hope was not a psychological state but a social investment: the person who had built relationships of loyalty and honest dealing had grounds for hoping that those relationships would support them in need. The wicked person who had extracted from others had no such social foundation; their hope was structurally groundless. The contrast is about social capital, not only eschatological expectation.</p>",
    "29": "<p><em>Derekh YHWH</em> (the way of the LORD) as a <em>ma'oz</em> (fortress/stronghold) for the <em>tam</em> (blameless/complete person) uses the same military-architectural vocabulary as the city-of-wealth image in v15. The difference: the blameless person&rsquo;s security is not in their own wealth but in alignment with YHWH&rsquo;s way. The word <em>mechitta</em> (ruin/destruction, H4288) for those who do evil captures the structural collapse of those whose life does not conform to the created order that YHWH&rsquo;s way describes. The covenant framework: living aligned with YHWH&rsquo;s character produces the security that human resources alone cannot.</p>",
    "30": "<p>The permanent rootedness of the righteous in contrast to the temporary residence of the wicked alludes to the land theology of Deuteronomy: the land was YHWH&rsquo;s gift held in trust by the covenant community, and continued residency depended on covenant faithfulness (Deut 4:25-26; 30:17-18). The wicked &ldquo;will not remain in the land&rdquo; (<em>lo' yishkenu 'aretz</em>) — not merely metaphorically but in the covenantal context of the promise that violation of the covenant would result in exile. This verse is the most directly land-theology verse in this chapter.</p>",
    "31": "<p>The productive mouth of the righteous that &ldquo;produces wisdom&rdquo; (<em>yanoov chokmah</em> — bears/produces as fruit, H5107) uses the agricultural vocabulary of fruit-bearing to describe the social function of the wise speaker. The tongue that will be &ldquo;cut off&rdquo; (<em>tikkareit</em>) uses the covenant curse language — <em>karet</em> (cutting off) was the term for the most severe form of divine punishment in the legal codes of Leviticus, applied to covenant violations (Lev 7:20; 18:29). The perverse tongue (<em>tahpukot</em>) that distorts the social order is being treated as a covenant violation in miniature.</p>",
    "32": "<p>The <em>da'at ratzon</em> (knowledge of what is pleasing/acceptable) attributed to the lips of the righteous is not merely aesthetic sensitivity but the social skill of discerning what the situation and the person require — the same quality praised in 25:11 (the fitly-spoken word). The knowledge of what is pleasing is the wisdom of social attunement: reading the moment, the person, and the community&rsquo;s needs accurately. The wicked person who speaks only what is perverse (<em>tahpukot</em>, distortions/perversions) lacks this social intelligence: their speech is calibrated not to the situation&rsquo;s needs but to their own advantage.</p>"
  },
  "11": {
    "1": "<p>False weights and dishonest scales (<em>mo'znei mirmah</em>, scales of deceit) were among the most commonly condemned commercial practices in the ANE. Deuteronomy 25:13-16 explicitly prohibits carrying two sets of weights (heavy for selling, light for buying); Leviticus 19:35-36 mandates accurate weights; Amos 8:5 describes the practice of the unscrupulous trader who waits for the sabbath to end so he can resume using dishonest measures. The accusation that such practices are <em>to'avat YHWH</em> (detestable to the LORD, an abomination) elevates commercial ethics to the realm of the sacral: economic fraud is not merely illegal but sacrilegious in the same category as idolatry. <em>Even shelemah</em> (an accurate/complete stone weight) was the required alternative.</p>",
    "2": "<p>The pride-shame pairing (<em>zadon, qallon</em>) in v2a reflects the honor-shame social psychology of the ancient world: <em>zadon</em> (presumption, arrogance, H2087) is the overreach that claims more social standing than one has earned or been granted. In an honor-based culture where social standing was negotiated through deference, performance, and recognition by one&rsquo;s social superiors, the arrogant person was attempting to seize honor without earning it — a fundamental social violation. The automatic consequence (<em>yavo' qalon</em> — disgrace comes) is not merely a moral observation but a social mechanism: communities actively shamed those who violated the protocols of honor-recognition.</p>",
    "3": "<p><em>Tummah yesharim</em> (the integrity of the upright) uses the <em>tom/tam</em> root — completeness/wholeness. The imagery of the guide (<em>tancheh</em>, will guide/lead, the shepherding verb) for integrity is a pastoral image: integrity acts as the shepherd for the person who possesses it, directing their path through complex moral terrain. The treachery of the faithless (<em>selef boge'dim</em>, the distortion of the treacherous) uses <em>selef</em> (H5558, the crooked, the perverse) as the anti-guide — a navigation system that leads actively in the wrong direction rather than simply failing to guide. The two groups are not merely differently successful; they are moving in opposite directions.</p>",
    "4": "<p>The day of wrath (<em>yom evrah</em>) is a theological idiom for divine judgment — the moment when YHWH&rsquo;s anger with wickedness is enacted. The wisdom tradition uses this as the framework for evaluating wealth: wealth has instrumental value in ordinary life (as 10:15 acknowledges) but is structurally useless before divine judgment. This is the wisdom tradition&rsquo;s version of the critique of wealth as ultimate security. The repeated pairing of wealth/righteousness around the deliverance-from-death frame (cf. 10:2) suggests a deliberate theological claim: righteousness (right-dealing, covenant loyalty) provides a form of security that wealth cannot.</p>",
    "5": "<p>The blameless person&rsquo;s <em>tzedaqah</em> (righteousness) making their way straight (<em>tiYasher derek</em> — will smooth/straighten their way) uses the road-preparation vocabulary of the ANE: before a royal journey, workers would clear and level the road. Applied to the moral life, &ldquo;straight way&rdquo; (<em>derekh yashar</em>) means a life without the obstacles created by social entanglements, broken trust, and moral debt. The wicked falling by their own wickedness (<em>be-rish'ato yippol</em>) describes the self-trapping quality of wrongdoing: each act of wickedness creates new social liabilities that accumulate into an eventual collapse.</p>",
    "6": "<p>The righteousness of the upright as a rescuer uses the <em>natzal</em> vocabulary (H5337, to snatch out, to deliver from danger) — the rescue imagery of the Psalter. In a context where legal jeopardy, debt bondage, and social enmity were constant threats to ordinary Israelite households, the language of rescue is concrete: the person whose record of right-dealing was known in the community had a social network that would advocate for them in difficulty. The treacherous (<em>boge'dim</em>) are trapped by their own <em>hawwah</em> (desire/craving/calamity) — the word carries both the meaning of desire and its destructive consequences.</p>",
    "7": "<p>The death of the wicked as the moment when their <em>tiqvah</em> (hope, expectation) perishes reflects the social understanding that hope requires a community that will remember and honor one&rsquo;s legacy. The wicked person, having built their life on extraction from others, has no community willing to sustain their memory; their hope — the expectation that they had accumulated enough influence to be remembered and honored — dies with them. The term <em>'onim</em> (wrongdoers, H202 — also the word for &ldquo;wealth/power,&rdquo; <em>'on</em>) suggests that the hope placed in material and social power is precisely the hope that fails.</p>",
    "8": "<p>The righteous being rescued from trouble (<em>tzarah</em>) and the wicked taking their place in it reflects the social mechanism of the scapegoat: someone must bear the consequences when social order breaks down, and it tends to be the wicked rather than the righteous (who have built the social capital of good relationships). The verse is an observation about social dynamics, not a guarantee: the righteous person&rsquo;s community connections tend to provide advocates and alternatives that the wicked person lacks. This is wisdom observation about how communal life tends to work, not divine promise about how it always works.</p>",
    "9": "<p>The godless person (<em>chanef</em>, H2611 — the profane, the hypocrite, the one who violates the sacred order) who destroys his neighbor through words (<em>befeh chanef yashchit re'ehu</em>) is using speech as a weapon in the social arena. In the gate-court context, accusations, depositions, and advocacy were the instruments of legal power; the godless person who weaponized words against a neighbor was engaging in the legal equivalent of assault. The righteous are saved through knowledge (<em>da'at</em>) — the practical wisdom to navigate the social and legal terrain without vulnerability to such attacks.</p>",
    "10": "<p>The city&rsquo;s rejoicing over the prosperity of the righteous (<em>ya'aloz qiryah bitzvach tzaddiqim</em>) reflects the ANE conception of the city as an organic community whose wellbeing was collective. In the city-gate economy, where trading, dispute resolution, and social negotiation happened in public, the prosperity of the upright produced visible public benefit: employment of others, hospitality, charitable giving, and the general security that came from having trustworthy people in leadership. The shout of joy at the perishing of the wicked (<em>be'aved resha'im rinnah</em>) is the community&rsquo;s public celebration of the removal of a destructive actor — a social response to justice that the modern west might find uncomfortable but that was normative in ancient communities.</p>",
    "11": "<p>The upright lifting up the city (<em>berakat yesharim tarum qaret</em>, by the blessing of the upright the city is elevated) is the positive formulation of communal flourishing: the <em>berakhah</em> (blessing) of the upright consists in their social contributions — honest trade, reliable word, generous hospitality, fair judicial testimony. These create the conditions in which the <em>qiryah</em> (city/community) can flourish. The demolishing of the city through the mouth of the wicked (the negative parallel) captures how much the ancient city depended on social trust: corrupt speech in the gate-court, false testimony, and slander were the forms of urban demolition available to the wicked.</p>",
    "12": "<p>Despising one&rsquo;s neighbor (<em>baz le-re'ehu</em>) is the social action of publicly dismissing another person&rsquo;s value — a form of shaming that in an honor culture was as damaging as physical assault. The <em>chasar lev</em> (one lacking in heart/judgment) who does this does not understand the social consequences: every public shaming creates a potential enemy and a public demonstration of the shamers&rsquo;s own unreliability. The person of <em>tevunah</em> (understanding/discernment) who stays silent is exercising the wisdom of restraint: not every perceived deficiency in another requires public announcement.</p>",
    "13": "<p><em>Holekh rakhil</em> (one who walks as a tale-bearer/gossip, H7400) — the person who goes around carrying private information for social advantage — is a specific character type in Israelite wisdom. The word <em>rakhil</em> is related to the tradesman (<em>rokhel</em>, merchant) who travels with goods; the gossip is the social merchant who trades in information. The contrast is the <em>ne'eman ru'ach</em> (faithful of spirit, reliable in spirit) who keeps confidence (<em>mekhasseh davar</em>, covers a matter). Confidentiality in the wisdom tradition is not mere discretion but covenant loyalty — the <em>ne'eman</em> is the trustworthy member of the community&rsquo;s inner circle whose reliability makes shared information possible.</p>",
    "14": "<p>The counsel of the many (<em>berov yo'atzim</em>) as the source of safety (<em>teshuat</em>, salvation/deliverance) reflects the ANE war-council practice: military decisions in the ancient Near East were made by councils of elders, advisors, and commanders rather than by monarchs acting unilaterally. The wisdom tradition applies this military governance principle to all significant decisions. The fall of a people without guidance (<em>ein tachbulet</em>, without the steering/piloting that gives direction to a ship) uses the navigation metaphor: the helmsmanship (<em>tachbulet</em>, related to <em>chevel</em>, rope/rigging) required by a ship is applied to the governance of human affairs. This is an explicitly political proverb about the wisdom of councils.</p>",
    "15": "<p>Guaranteeing for a stranger (<em>arev zar</em>) — co-signing a loan or pledge for someone outside one&rsquo;s social network — was consistently condemned in Proverbs (cf. 6:1-5; 17:18; 20:16; 27:13) because the accountability mechanisms that made loan guarantee manageable (community membership, reputation enforcement, social pressure to repay) did not apply to strangers. The <em>orev</em> (guarantor/pledge-giver) who gave surety for a stranger was extending the community&rsquo;s trust-infrastructure beyond its social reach. The person who hated such pledges (<em>sonek teqi'ot</em>) was making the rational social calculation that the risk exceeded any benefit.</p>",
    "16": "<p>A gracious woman (<em>'eshet chen</em>, a woman of grace/favor) gaining honor reflects the honor-acquisition mechanisms available to Israelite women: <em>chen</em> (grace, favor, the quality that attracts goodwill) was a recognized form of social capital that generated honor through relationship rather than through force. The comparison with ruthless men who gain only wealth (<em>'aritzim yitmeku 'osher</em>) places two modes of honor-acquisition against each other: the relational/personal mode (grace) and the forceful/economic mode (ruthless wealth-getting). Wealth is a lesser form of social capital than the relational goodwill generated by grace.</p>",
    "17": "<p>The <em>ish chesed</em> (man of covenant-loyalty/loving-kindness) who benefits himself through his <em>chesed</em> is the counter-intuitive wisdom insight: the investment in others that covenant loyalty requires returns to the investor in the form of social capital, reciprocity, and community protection. The word <em>gomel</em> (H1580, benefits, deals kindly with) is the primary verb of covenant action — to deal with someone according to <em>chesed</em>. The cruel person (<em>'akhzari</em>) who harms himself by his cruelty illustrates the boomerang quality of social destructiveness: each act of cruelty closes doors of reciprocity.</p>",
    "18": "<p><em>Pa'ulat shaqer</em> (deceptive wage/work) earned by the wicked is contrasted with <em>emet</em> (sure reward/true wage) for whoever sows righteousness. The agricultural imagery of sowing (<em>zore'a</em>) righteousness applies the harvest principle to social action: what one invests in the soil of the community — honest dealing, covenant loyalty, care for the poor — is the seed that produces the crop of genuine reward. The deceptive wage is the income that appears to satisfy but carries the hidden cost of social and divine accountability, making it ultimately unsatisfying and unsafe.</p>",
    "19": "<p>Genuine (<em>ken</em>, H3651, rightly/truly) righteousness as the path to life uses the directional imagery of the road again: <em>tzedaqah lecha chayyim</em> (righteousness toward/for life). The pursuit of evil as a path toward one&rsquo;s own death (<em>lemovet mevaqqesh nefesho</em> — pursues his own <em>nefesh</em>/soul/life toward death) is the self-destructive movement of the person whose moral direction is inverted. The person pursuing evil is in the position of the farmer who keeps moving away from his field: each step makes the harvest less accessible, until the pursuit becomes irreversibly self-defeating.</p>",
    "20": "<p>The <em>to'avat YHWH</em> (abomination to the LORD) applied to those with crooked hearts (<em>'iqqeshei-lev</em>) and the <em>retzon YHWH</em> (delight of the LORD) for those whose ways are blameless (<em>temimei derekh</em>) frames the language of cultic acceptability — the language used for sacrifices being acceptable or unacceptable — and applies it to moral character and behavior. This is the wisdom tradition&rsquo;s consistent move: what the cult treats as ritual categories (acceptable/detestable) are at root moral categories. A person of crooked heart who brings a sacrifice is offering an abomination; a person of blameless way who has no sacrifice is YHWH&rsquo;s delight.</p>",
    "21": "<p>The oath formula <em>yad le-yad</em> (hand to hand, meaning: &ldquo;you may count on it&rdquo; — the handshake pledge) introduces the assurance that the wicked will not go unpunished. This is the wisdom tradition&rsquo;s counter-testimony against the apparent success of the wicked: despite appearances, YHWH&rsquo;s justice is certain. The contrast is the offspring of the righteous escaping (<em>zera' tzaddiqim nimlat</em>) — the generational dimension of righteousness: the righteous person&rsquo;s descendants inherit the social capital, community goodwill, and divine blessing that the parent built. The family as the unit of moral consequence is central to the ancient worldview.</p>",
    "22": "<p>The pig (<em>chazir</em>) wearing a gold ring (<em>nezem zahav</em>) is a deliberate juxtaposition of value and inappropriateness. The pig was the paradigmatic unclean animal of Leviticus 11:7-8 — not merely impure for eating but associated with Gentile idolatry, the worst form of social pollution in the Israelite world-view. A beautiful woman who lacks discretion (<em>sar-ta'am</em>, turns away from good sense) is the same juxtaposition: the external ornament (beauty) makes the internal deficiency (<em>sar ta'am</em>, lack of judgment) more striking rather than concealing it, because the ornament and the beast it adorns are fundamentally incongruous.</p>",
    "23": "<p>The desire of the righteous (<em>ta'avat tzaddiqim</em>) ending only in good and the hope of the wicked bringing wrath (<em>'evrah</em>) frames the same eschatological/teleological contrast as 10:28. The use of desire/hope vocabulary makes the contrast personal: what one wants eventually shapes what one receives. In the covenantal framework, the righteous person&rsquo;s desire is oriented toward the community&rsquo;s flourishing and YHWH&rsquo;s provision; this desire aligns with the direction of creation and so finds its good. The wicked person&rsquo;s hope is oriented toward extraction from the community; this misalignment produces the divine wrath that corrects the disorder.</p>",
    "24": "<p>The paradox of the generous giver who increases while the hoarder decreases reflects the counter-intuitive economics of the covenant community. In the peasant subsistence economy of ancient Israel, the instinct was to hoard against scarcity; the proverb challenges this instinct with the social observation that generosity creates reciprocal social bonds that protect against scarcity more effectively than hoarding does. The generous person (<em>mefazar</em>, one who scatters/gives widely) builds a network of obligation and goodwill; the withholder (<em>choseh miyosher</em>) isolates himself from that network. Community investment is more economically efficient than individual hoarding in a reciprocal economy.</p>",
    "25": "<p>The <em>nefesh berakha</em> (soul/person of blessing, the generous-spirited person) being made rich (<em>tidushen</em>, enriched/fattened — the word for making prosperous through abundance) is the positive formulation of v24. The one who waters others (<em>meravveh</em>) will himself be watered — the irrigation metaphor applies the agricultural law of reciprocity: the canal system required collective maintenance, and those who maintained the canals for others benefited from the water flow themselves. Palestinian water management was communal, making this metaphor directly comprehensible to Israelite hearers.</p>",
    "26": "<p>The cursing of the grain-hoarder by the people (<em>yiqquvehu le'om</em>) reflects the social expectation in the ancient economy that those with surplus had obligations to share it with those in need. Grain-hoarding in a famine context was not merely socially unpopular but was treated as a form of economic violence against the community. The blessing on the seller (<em>vevirakhah le-rosh mashbir</em>) is the community&rsquo;s honor-recognition of the person who met the social obligation. This is the honor-shame economy operating through the mechanism of market ethics: selling at fair price in time of shortage generates social honor; exploitation generates the curse.</p>",
    "27": "<p>Seeking good (<em>shocher tov</em>, the earnest seeker of good) receiving favor (<em>ratzon</em>, H7522, goodwill/acceptance) and the pursuit of evil producing evil (<em>rav'ah tevo'ennu</em> — evil will come upon him) is the moral ecology of the wisdom tradition. <em>Ratzon</em> is the term used for the king&rsquo;s favor (and by extension YHWH&rsquo;s favor) — the goodwill of the most powerful that protects and enables the person who has earned it. The orientation of one&rsquo;s seeking determines what one finds: the universe is structured such that genuine good-seeking eventually encounters what it seeks.</p>",
    "28": "<p>The folly of trusting in wealth (<em>botea' be'ashro</em>) is evaluated through the agricultural contrast: the fallen wealthy (<em>yippol</em>) vs. the righteous flourishing like a fresh branch (<em>ke'aleh yiphrach</em>). The evergreen branch (<em>'aleh</em>) that continues to grow uses the visual contrast of the dried-up withered branch (what wealth looks like when it fails) against the fresh growing one (what righteousness looks like). In the Palestinian climate, the difference between a living and dead branch was visibly dramatic: the living branch was unmistakably green, the dead branch unmistakably dry. The contrast is designed to be visually recognizable.</p>",
    "29": "<p>Bringing trouble on one&rsquo;s household (<em>oker beito</em>, the one who destroys/troubles his household) inheriting wind is the agricultural futility metaphor: the harvest of the one who destroys his own household is the insubstantial, inedible air — wealth that cannot feed. The household (<em>bayit</em>) in the ancient economy was the basic economic unit: the farm, the animals, the workshop, and the dwelling were all part of the <em>bayit</em>. To destroy one&rsquo;s own household through foolish action was not merely personal ruin but the dissolution of the community&rsquo;s most basic economic structure. The fool ending up serving the wise (<em>ve'evil ya'avod lechakham-lev</em>) describes the reversal of expected social status.</p>",
    "30": "<p>The <em>'etz chayyim</em> (tree of life) applied to the fruit of the righteous is a deliberate Eden allusion (Gen 2:9; 3:22, 24): the tree of life in the garden was the source of unending vitality, access to which was lost in the expulsion. In Proverbs, the tree-of-life imagery recurs for wisdom (3:18) and fulfilled desire (13:12). The righteous person&rsquo;s fruitfulness (<em>peri tzaddiq</em>) is identified with this life-sustaining tree: the moral life produces the kind of social vitality that the garden&rsquo;s tree represented. The wisdom winner (<em>chakham nefashot</em>, the wise one who wins souls) connects this to the Proverbs tradition of wisdom as the means of drawing others into life.</p>",
    "31": "<p>The conditional argument of v31 (if the righteous receive their just deserts on earth, how much more the wicked) reflects the <em>qal wahomer</em> (light to heavy) argument form — a standard rabbinical hermeneutical principle, here deployed as a wisdom argument. The claim is not that the righteous suffer (the word <em>yeshullam</em> — receive their due/reward — is positive in sense) but that if even the righteous must face consequences for their actions within creation&rsquo;s moral order, the wicked face far more. 1 Peter 4:18 quotes this verse in the context of the judgment that begins with God&rsquo;s household — a NT use that extends the <em>qal wahomer</em> into eschatological register.</p>"
  },
  "12": {
    "1": "<p>The love of discipline (<em>'ohev musar</em>) as love of knowledge (<em>'ohev da'at</em>) uses the educational vocabulary of the Israelite household. <em>Musar</em> (H4148, instruction/discipline/correction) includes both verbal teaching and physical correction — the formation process through which the household transmitted its practical wisdom to the next generation. The person who loves the process of formation is the person who will ultimately possess the product (knowledge). The one who hates correction (<em>sone' tokhechat</em>) is described with the stark label <em>ba'ar</em> (H1198, brutish/dumb, like an animal) — the person who has not been differentiated from the purely instinctual life through formation.</p>",
    "2": "<p>The <em>tov</em> (good man) obtaining YHWH&rsquo;s favor (<em>ratzon</em>) and the <em>'ish zimmot</em> (man of evil schemes/devices) being condemned uses the judicial vocabulary of divine judgment: <em>yarshi'a</em> (H7561, to condemn, to declare guilty — the opposite of <em>hitzdiq</em>, to justify/declare righteous). In the gate-court context where verdicts were pronounced and social standing adjudicated, being condemned by YHWH was the ultimate verdict — one that transcended any human court&rsquo;s ability to reverse. The <em>ratzon</em> (favor) of YHWH was the social equivalent of royal favor, providing the protection and access that made flourishing possible.</p>",
    "3": "<p>The rootedness of the righteous (<em>shoreshet tzaddiqim lo' timmot</em>, the root of the righteous will not be shaken) uses the arboricultural vocabulary of deep-rooted stability: a tree with deep roots survives storms that destroy shallow-rooted ones. Applied to the household economics of ancient Israel, this image has concrete force: the household (<em>bayit</em>) with deep roots in the community — long-standing relationships, established reputation, inherited land — was structurally resistant to misfortune in a way that the newly established household was not. Wickedness provides no such rootedness because it alienates rather than builds the community relationships that are the actual substrate of stability.</p>",
    "4": "<p><em>'Eshet chayil</em> (a capable/excellent wife, a woman of strength/valor) is the same phrase used in Proverbs 31:10 for the idealized household manager of the book&rsquo;s concluding poem, and in Ruth 3:11 where Boaz praises Ruth. The word <em>chayil</em> (H2428, valor/strength/capacity) is primarily used in military contexts (an army of valor, a mighty warrior) but is applied here and in ch. 31 to the domestic strength of the woman who manages the household economy. The crown metaphor for the capable wife is the honor-recognition vocabulary: she provides the social prestige that makes her husband&rsquo;s public standing possible. The antithesis — the shameful wife as decay in his bones — is the corresponding social destruction.</p>",
    "5": "<p>The plans of the righteous as <em>mishpat</em> (justice/judgment) and the schemes of the wicked as <em>mirmah</em> (deceit) places the two orientations in their judicial context: the righteous person plans in accordance with the judicial norms of the community (<em>mishpat</em> = the ordinance, what has been judged to be right), while the wicked person plans in ways that subvert those norms through deceit. In the ancient community, planning that violated community norms was identifiable and correctable; planning that concealed its violations through deceit was the more dangerous category because it evaded the community&rsquo;s accountability mechanisms.</p>",
    "6": "<p>The words of the wicked as an ambush for blood (<em>divrei resha'im erev-dam</em>) uses the legal vocabulary of the gate-court: lying testimony and false accusation were forms of violence that could result in capital punishment. The connection between speech and bloodshed is literal in the legal context, not merely metaphorical: false witness could get an innocent person killed (cf. the case of Naboth in 1 Kgs 21 and the commandment against false witness in Deut 19:16-21). The mouth of the upright as a deliverer (<em>pi yesharim yatzillem</em>) is the positive use of the same legal context: reliable, accurate speech in the gate-court delivers people from unjust outcomes.</p>",
    "7": "<p>The overthrow of the wicked (<em>hafokh resha'im</em>) and their disappearance contrasted with the standing of the house of the righteous (<em>beit tzaddiqim ya'amod</em>) reflects the social permanence that institutional trust creates. The <em>bayit</em> (household) that stands is not merely the physical building but the entire social institution of the family — its name, its reputation, its trading relationships, its land tenure. A household built on right-dealing has stakeholders in the community who have an interest in its continuation; a household built on wickedness has enemies who benefit from its fall.</p>",
    "8": "<p>Praise according to wisdom (<em>lefi sichlo yuhallal-'ish</em>, according to his good sense a man is praised) reflects the honor-allocation mechanism of the ancient community: <em>sekhel</em> (H7922, good sense, insight, the ability to understand situations correctly) was the quality that generated public praise in the gate-court context. The person with <em>sekhel</em> was publicly recognized because their counsel, decisions, and speech consistently produced good outcomes visible to the community. The twisted mind (<em>'iqqesh-lev</em>) being despised is the mirror: the community withholds honor from the person whose reasoning consistently distorts and deceives.</p>",
    "9": "<p>The preference for humble standing with food over displaying status without substance reflects the social-display economy of the ancient world. In an honor-shame culture, the temptation to maintain appearances beyond one&rsquo;s means was powerful: social standing was visible and public, and the shame of perceived poverty was severe. The proverb counters this with the practical wisdom that real sustenance (food) is more valuable than social performance. The person of humble standing (<em>niqleh</em>, lightly esteemed) who has a servant (<em>ve'eved lo</em>) is better positioned than the person who presents himself as important (<em>mitkabed</em>, glorifies himself) but lacks bread. Material sufficiency trumps social performance.</p>",
    "10": "<p>The righteous man who cares for the wellbeing of his animal (<em>yode'a tzaddiq nefesh behemto</em>, the righteous man knows the <em>nefesh</em>/life of his animal) represents an unusual extension of moral concern in the ANE world. Most ancient Near Eastern wisdom literature shows no interest in animal welfare; the Israelite tradition, rooted in the covenant community&rsquo;s obligations to all living things (Deut 22:4; 25:4), treats care for working animals as a moral indicator. The inversion — even the compassion of the wicked is cruel (<em>ve-rachamei resha'im 'akhzari</em>) — suggests that cruelty to animals is diagnostic of the wicked person&rsquo;s character: their most compassionate action is cruel by the standard of genuine care.</p>",
    "11": "<p>The agricultural basis of the Israelite economy is explicit in the exhortation to work one&rsquo;s land (<em>'oveid 'admatho</em>). The land was the primary productive asset of the Israelite household; its cultivation was the central economic activity. &ldquo;Chasing empty things&rdquo; (<em>meredeph reqim</em>, pursuing empty/worthless things) refers to commercial or social activities that distracted from agricultural work — trading ventures, mercenary service, or the pursuit of wealth through other means. The wisdom tradition consistently valued the patient, grounded work of land cultivation over speculative wealth-seeking. Lack of good sense (<em>chasar-lev</em>) is the diagnosis of those who prefer the exciting chase to the reliable field.</p>",
    "12": "<p>The craving of the wicked for the catch of evil people (<em>chamad rasha' metzod ra'im</em>) reflects the predatory economy of opportunistic wealth transfer: the wicked covet not just wealth but the specific form of wealth that others have taken through force — joining networks of exploitation. The contrast — the root of the righteous produces its own fruit (<em>shoreshet tzaddiqim yitten</em>) — uses the tree-root metaphor of 12:3: the righteous person&rsquo;s established position in the community produces its own sustainable yield, not dependent on what others have seized. Self-generating productivity vs. derivative predation.</p>",
    "13": "<p>Being trapped by the sins of one&rsquo;s lips (<em>bephesha' sefatayim moqesh ra'</em>) places speech in the context of the gate-court legal system: the evil person&rsquo;s speech creates the evidence for his own legal destruction. In the Israelite legal system, speech in court was self-constituting: to make a false accusation was to risk the punishment one intended for the accused (Deut 19:19). But more broadly, the person who speaks wickedly in the community generates a record of untrustworthiness that eventually catches up with them. The righteous escaping from trouble (<em>mi-tzarah yatza' tzaddiq</em>) is the counterpoint: the reliable social record of the righteous provides the community advocacy that enables escape.</p>",
    "14": "<p>The fruit of one&rsquo;s words (<em>peri fi-'ish</em>, the fruit of a man&rsquo;s mouth) as the source of satisfaction uses the harvest vocabulary: speech is productive labor whose fruit returns to the speaker. This is the positive version of the self-creating-trap principle of v13: speech that builds community, communicates accurately, and serves the neighbor creates the social capital that eventually returns to the speaker as support and reward. The parallel — the work of a man&rsquo;s hands returns to him (<em>gemul yadev yashuv lo</em>) — applies the same harvest principle to physical labor: the economy of return governs both speech and action.</p>",
    "15": "<p>The self-validating quality of the fool&rsquo;s perception (<em>derekh 'evil yashar be'einav</em>, the fool&rsquo;s way is straight in his own eyes) is the wisdom tradition&rsquo;s diagnosis of the closed feedback loop: the fool&rsquo;s internal judgment system validates only his own perspective. In a community where reputation was built through the perception of others and where wise elders and parents provided the external reality-check that shaped judgment, the fool who rejected all external correction had cut himself off from the community&rsquo;s calibration system. The wise person who listens to counsel (<em>shome'a le'etzah</em>) uses the community&rsquo;s collective perception to correct the distortions of individual perspective.</p>",
    "16": "<p>The fool&rsquo;s immediate disclosure of his annoyance (<em>'evvil beyo yivvada' ka'so</em>, on that very day the fool&rsquo;s vexation is known) reflects the honor-shame dynamic of emotional self-regulation. In a community where face-to-face interactions were the primary social medium, the person who could not conceal irritation was displaying a failure of self-mastery that others could exploit: showing annoyance invites the person who caused it to repeat the provocation. The prudent person who overlooks an insult (<em>'arum khoseh qallon</em>, the prudent person covers/hides shame) is practicing the social discipline of not giving the provocateur the satisfaction of a visible response.</p>",
    "17": "<p>The legal context of &ldquo;witness&rdquo; (<em>'ed</em>) terminology in vv17-19 is the gate-court where community disputes were adjudicated. The <em>'ed 'emeth</em> (truthful witness) who breathes out (<em>yafiaach</em>, to breathe out, to express) honest testimony (<em>tzadeq</em>, what is right/just) is contrasted with the false witness (<em>'ed shaqer</em>) who exhales deceit (<em>mirmah</em>). The respiratory metaphor for testimony is revealing: testimony in the oral culture was breath — the living word that carried weight precisely because it was a person&rsquo;s exhalation, their committed speech. False testimony corrupted the breath itself.</p>",
    "18": "<p>Words that pierce like a sword (<em>betach charvot</em>, rashly/carelessly cutting with a sword) uses the weapon metaphor for the harm done by reckless speech in the community. The connection is not abstract: false accusations, careless depositions, and divisive speech in the gate-court could result in punishment, social exclusion, or death for the accused. The tongue of the wise as the healer (<em>lashon chakhamim marpeh</em>) is the counter-image: speech calibrated to accuracy and care has the physician&rsquo;s function in the community — it diagnoses and corrects disorders rather than inflicting wounds.</p>",
    "19": "<p>The permanence of truth (<em>sefat 'emet tikkon la'ad</em>, lips of truth stand firm forever) and the momentary quality of the lying tongue (<em>lashon shaqer reqa' 'ad-'argia'</em>, for just a moment) reflect the social observation that truth outlasts lies because truth is congruent with the way things are: the community&rsquo;s memory eventually corrects false accounts by comparison with lived experience. Lies require ongoing maintenance — each lie creates new inconsistencies that require further lies — while truth requires no maintenance because it is self-consistent. The <em>la'ad</em> (forever/perpetually) of truthful lips is the temporal stability that comes from congruence with reality.</p>",
    "20": "<p>Deceit (<em>mirmah</em>) filling the heart of those who devise evil (<em>be-lev choreshei ra'</em>, in the heart of those who plow evil) uses agricultural vocabulary for planning: to plow (<em>charash</em>) evil is to prepare the ground for its growth. The contrast — peace-counselors finding joy (<em>le-yo'atzei shalom simchah</em>) — uses the political vocabulary of negotiation and peacemaking. In the ANE context where inter-community disputes were mediated through councils of elders, the person who counseled peace rather than conflict was the social benefactor who created conditions for communal flourishing. <em>Simchah</em> (joy) as their reward is both personal and communal: the community rejoices over peacemaking.</p>",
    "21": "<p>No harm (<em>lo' ye'unneh</em>, nothing evil will happen to, it will not be sent against) to the righteous and the filling of the wicked with trouble (<em>resha'im male'u ra'</em>) reflects the protective social network that righteousness builds. The righteous person has invested in relationships of mutual obligation; the community is invested in their wellbeing. The wicked person has broken or exploited those relationships; the community is invested in their accountability. The verse is not a naive claim that righteous people never suffer but a social observation about who the community rallies around when trouble comes.</p>",
    "22": "<p>Lying lips as abomination to YHWH (<em>to'avat YHWH sefatei shaqer</em>) and the faithful as YHWH&rsquo;s delight (<em>retzon YHWH 'osei 'emunah</em>) applies the cultic language of acceptable/unacceptable offerings to the practice of speech. <em>Emunah</em> (H530, faithfulness, reliability, the quality of being steady and trustworthy) is the covenant-loyalty virtue in its practical form: the person who does what they say, whose word can be relied upon. This faithfulness in speech is YHWH&rsquo;s delight — a stronger term than mere approval, suggesting the pleasure of seeing the created order functioning as designed.</p>",
    "23": "<p>The prudent person who conceals what he knows (<em>'arum kosse da'at</em>) and the fool whose heart broadcasts its folly (<em>lev kesilim yiqra' 'ivvelet</em>) uses the acoustic metaphor of the town crier (<em>qara'</em>, to call out/proclaim) for the fool&rsquo;s inability to keep his counsel. In the ANE political context, knowledge was power, and the strategic non-disclosure of information was a form of political intelligence. The wise advisor in the royal court kept information until the right moment; the fool disclosed everything immediately. This is not merely about personal discretion but about the strategic use of knowledge in the communal context.</p>",
    "24": "<p>The diligent hand ruling (<em>yad charuzim timshol</em>) and the lazy person being put to forced labor (<em>'atzel yihyeh lemass</em>) uses the political vocabulary of governance and corvée labor. <em>Mas</em> (H4522, forced labor, the labor tax levied on subject populations) was the most degraded form of social position: in ancient Israel, Canaanites were subjected to <em>mas</em> (Josh 16:10; 1 Kgs 9:21), and the fear of being reduced to forced labor was a powerful social motivation. The verse frames diligence as the difference between ruling and being enslaved — social governance or social subjugation.</p>",
    "25": "<p>Anxiety in the heart (<em>de'agah be-lev-'ish</em>) weighing it down (<em>yash-chennah</em>, H7812 — bow it down, cause it to sink) and the good word (<em>dabar tov</em>) making it glad (<em>yesammechenah</em>) reflects the social-psychological function of speech in the ancient oral community. Spoken word was not primarily a vehicle for information transfer but a social action that had immediate effect on the listener&rsquo;s emotional state. The <em>dabar tov</em> (good word, encouraging word, word that accurately names something positive in the other person&rsquo;s situation) functioned as a concrete social benefit. Paul&rsquo;s instruction to &ldquo;encourage one another&rdquo; (1 Thess 5:11) stands in this tradition.</p>",
    "26": "<p>The righteous man guiding his neighbor well (<em>yather me-re'ehu tzaddiq</em>, the righteous man searches out the best path for his neighbor) uses the shepherding/pathfinding vocabulary: the <em>tather</em> (H3498, to leave over, to go beyond — meaning here to serve as guide/scout) for the neighbor. The social function of the righteous in the community is directional: they help others find the path. The way of the wicked leading others astray (<em>derekh resha'im tat'em</em>, the way of the wicked causes them to go astray) is the corresponding negative: the wicked person&rsquo;s example and influence draws others off their path rather than pointing them toward it.</p>",
    "27": "<p>The lazy man who does not bother to prepare his game (<em>lo' yacharo'k 'atzel tzeydo</em> — the lazy man does not roast/prepare what he hunted) is the agricultural/hunting analog of the sluggard proverbs. The hunt has been successful; the preparation has not been done. This describes not the person who fails to pursue resources but the one who cannot convert the resources they obtain into usable form — the last-step failure. In the ancient household economy, the conversion of raw materials (game, grain, olives) into food required continuous labor; the failure at the conversion step was as costly as the failure at the acquisition step. The <em>chozen 'adam charuts</em> (wealth of a diligent man) being precious contrasts with this waste.</p>",
    "28": "<p>The path of righteousness (<em>be-'orach tzedaqah chayyim</em>, in the path of righteousness is life) and the road of that path having no death (<em>vedarekh netivah 'al-mavet</em>) is the most striking conclusion to ch. 12. The claim that the path of righteousness leads away from death entirely — not merely to longer life but to a place where death itself is absent — exceeds the ordinary retribution theology and points toward the eschatological reading: the life promised to the righteous is not simply a longer temporal life but a qualitative life that participates in the life of YHWH who has no death. This verse anticipates the NT development of the <em>'orach chayyim</em> (path of life) as the way that leads to resurrection.</p>"
  }
}

def main():
    existing = load_comm('mkt-context', 'proverbs')
    merge_comm(existing, PROVERBS)
    save_comm('mkt-context', 'proverbs', existing)
    total = sum(len(vv) for vv in PROVERBS.values())
    parts = ', '.join(f'ch{ch}={len(PROVERBS[ch])}' for ch in sorted(PROVERBS, key=int))
    print(f'Proverbs 10-12 mkt-context: {total} verses written ({parts}).')

if __name__ == '__main__':
    main()
